	<div id="id1eb5" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="Weddings: worst and only use of the word “joyous”" width="609" class="title" src="../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/8c40d249"/><span class="title">Weddings: worst and only use of the word “joyous”</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>, <span>on November 5, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id1eb6" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../city/tag/consumerism/#selected-tag"><span>consumerism</span></a><span id="id1eb7">, </span></span><span><a href="../../city/tag/weddings/#selected-tag"><span>weddings</span></a><span id="id1eb8">, </span></span><span><a href="../../city/tag/shopping/#selected-tag"><span>shopping</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p>Being of highly marriageable age, MrLittlePants and I get invited to weddings. We&#8217;re in the special &#8220;friends&#8221; category. The people who, in the imaginary small wedding that everyone says they want, would be the only ones there.</p>


	<p>As a once and future wedding guest, I&#8217;d like to call bullshit on a few things, most importantly, <a href="http://ask.metafilter.com/mefi/49924#757928">this claim</a>:</p>


	<blockquote>
		<p>People, or anyway most people, want to give on a joyous occasion; I wouldn&#8217;t take [the gift registry] option away from them.</p>
	</blockquote>


	<p style="float:right"><img src="/pictures/store.jpg" alt="" /></p>


	<p>As a &#8220;most people,&#8221; and one with particularly little regard for keeping up appearances (at least on these pages), I&#8217;d like to tell all the brides-to-be out there that the guests of your own generation are actually gritting their teeth about practically every aspect of your wedding, especially the registry.</p>


	<p>This shouldn&#8217;t need pointing out. There&#8217;s a whole genre of <a href="http://technically.us/doc/articles/2006/04/24/the-reality-of-television">reality television</a> devoted to the monstrosity of brides. But on the other side, the &#8220;joyous&#8221; side, they&#8217;ve got a machine that would make the Republican Party jealous.</p>


	<p>They&#8217;ve got wedding magazines, Web sites, and even some tradition. Most importantly, they&#8217;ve got multitudes of people whose livelihoods depend on maximizing the consumerization of weddings. It&#8217;s an industry, by golly, and each participant works to expand the glorious culture of wedding expenditures <em>because it increases their salaries</em>.</p>


	<p>Bridal registries have become superfluous in this era of couples over the age of twenty-five already having dishes, but the Internet somehow modernized the concept into a disgusting bridal-freudian-supervillian disaster.</p>


	<p>Usually the Internet improves things, to a drastic degree. But in weddings, the Web&#8217;s famed wheel-greasing has reduced a heartwarming tradition to the emotional involvement of ordering office supplies.</p>


	<p>When you receive a wedding invitation, with a <em>separate</em> card, that links to a wedding web site, that links to your gift registry, (this bride can definitely <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King_Bowser#Platformers">beat Bowser</a>) it starts to feel a lot like taxation without representation. Particularly for the gays, during wartime.</p>


	<p>Worse, online registry fulfillment is as inefficient as a government. Who pays full price when shopping on the Internet, plus $15 for shipping? Wedding invitees. No one else is in such a compromised position.</p>


	<p>What about just bringing the gift with you? According to <a href="http://ask.metafilter.com/mefi/49924#759106">one registry booster</a>, &#8220;actually, it&#8217;s courteous to not bring a wrapped gift to an event&#8212;someone has to drag it home, it risks getting lost, stolen, cards go missing.&#8221;</p>


	<p>Oh my God. Someone has to &#8220;drag&#8221; your gift home. This is what happens when lovers of Internet registries go off message. In one subordinate clause they&#8217;re touting tradition, while in the next they&#8217;re screeching for you to <em>just type in your credit card number, already</em>.</p>


	<p>Ladies, uhh&#8230; Can you see that you are running weddings for everyone?</p>


	<p><strong>Update:</strong> The related ad links on the sidebar are mighty interesting, particularly the one for setting up a <strong>cash</strong> registry. I say go for it; rock bottom is better than half-way there.</p></div>
